00:57:09.470 --> 00:57:12.210
But I was wondering, you
kept talking about language,

00:57:12.210 --> 00:57:13.810
and I kept wondering,
well this is--

00:57:13.810 --> 00:57:15.476
you're talking about
language but you're

00:57:15.476 --> 00:57:16.610
talking about English.

00:57:16.610 --> 00:57:20.230
Have you explored anything with
other linguists about problems

00:57:20.230 --> 00:57:23.390
like this that are similar
in other either Latin based

00:57:23.390 --> 00:57:25.235
languages, or not
Latin based languages?

00:57:26.240 --> 00:57:29.440
STEVEN PINKER: I imagine
that much of the advice

00:57:29.440 --> 00:57:30.880
would carry over.

00:57:30.880 --> 00:57:35.100
We all comprehend things
using the same brains

00:57:35.100 --> 00:57:38.070
and the advantage of
allowing your reader

00:57:38.070 --> 00:57:43.350
to visualize something as
opposed to just spooning out

00:57:43.350 --> 00:57:46.460
cliches surely holds
in every language.

00:57:46.460 --> 00:57:52.310
And indeed, classic style which
is the central image from which

00:57:52.310 --> 00:57:58.369
a lot of these bits of advice
are theorems, are implications.

00:57:58.369 --> 00:57:59.785
According to Thomas
and Turner, it

00:57:59.785 --> 00:58:02.640
was actually invented by
the great French essayists

00:58:02.640 --> 00:58:03.830
of the 17th century.

00:58:03.830 --> 00:58:06.220
And even though French
style is in many ways

00:58:06.220 --> 00:58:08.760
different from English
style, they credit writers

00:58:08.760 --> 00:58:12.700
like Descartes, and
[INAUDIBLE] with coming up

00:58:12.700 --> 00:58:15.310
with this conceit of pretending
that you're describing

00:58:15.310 --> 00:58:18.200
a world all the differences
between the French language

00:58:18.200 --> 00:58:20.700
and English language
clearly did not matter.

00:58:20.700 --> 00:58:25.020
There are, to be sure, there
must be some differences,

00:58:25.020 --> 00:58:31.020
especially when it comes to the
way in which the linearization

00:58:31.020 --> 00:58:35.170
of words in syntax conveys
a tangled web of ideas.

00:58:35.170 --> 00:58:38.330
Because there there are some
obvious cross linguistic

00:58:38.330 --> 00:58:39.150
differences.

00:58:39.150 --> 00:58:41.734
In German for example,
the verb comes

00:58:41.734 --> 00:58:43.900
at the end of the sentence
instead of the beginning.

00:58:43.900 --> 00:58:49.090
And so the tips on how to engage
the reader's mind in real time

00:58:49.090 --> 00:58:51.450
would have to be
modified accordingly.

00:58:51.450 --> 00:58:53.750
I'll find out when
this book is translated

00:58:53.750 --> 00:58:56.880
into other languages
how many questions I get

00:58:56.880 --> 00:58:59.220
and how the translator
will deal with them.

00:58:59.220 --> 00:59:03.950
As far as the words-- new
words like incentivize go,

00:59:03.950 --> 00:59:06.850
incentivize actually turns
out to be a pretty useful word

00:59:06.850 --> 00:59:10.420
because there's
no-- remember, one

00:59:10.420 --> 00:59:14.040
of the guidelines for writing
is omit needless words.

00:59:14.040 --> 00:59:17.210
And if you say something
like layout incentives for,

00:59:17.210 --> 00:59:19.260
that's an awful lot
of needless words.

00:59:19.260 --> 00:59:25.270
Moreover, when you compress
a phrase into a verb,

00:59:25.270 --> 00:59:27.780
it adds a semantic difference.

00:59:27.780 --> 00:59:30.770
Namely that it implies
that there's something

00:59:30.770 --> 00:59:33.870
that you are directly
and immediately causing.

00:59:33.870 --> 00:59:38.010
And as we become more aware
that policy changes that

00:59:38.010 --> 00:59:41.450
may have been thought up
and implemented to achieve

00:59:41.450 --> 00:59:45.580
some abstract goal may
have perverse results.

00:59:45.580 --> 00:59:47.700
Because as soon as they
lay out the incentives,

00:59:47.700 --> 00:59:49.440
people will follow
the incentives.

00:59:49.440 --> 00:59:51.210
Perhaps doing
something the opposite

00:59:51.210 --> 00:59:54.010
of what the writers
of legislation intend,

00:59:54.010 --> 00:59:57.540
the verb incentivize reminds
you that in doing something

00:59:57.540 --> 01:00:02.270
you are automatically changing
the landscape of options

01:00:02.270 --> 01:00:04.870
and so it conveys an
additional meaning

01:00:04.870 --> 01:00:06.867
above and beyond
creating incentives for.

01:00:06.867 --> 01:00:08.325
AUDIENCE: Right it
makes it active.

01:00:09.229 --> 01:00:11.270
STEVEN PINKER: Exactly,
it's active, it's direct,

01:00:11.270 --> 01:00:11.940
it's causal.

01:00:11.940 --> 01:00:13.815
AUDIENCE: As opposed to
providing incentives.

01:00:14.392 --> 01:00:15.350
STEVEN PINKER: Exactly.

01:00:15.350 --> 01:00:17.310
AUDIENCE: Which does
sound kind of passive.

01:00:17.310 --> 01:00:19.359
I've gotten over it,
it was 15 years ago.

01:00:19.359 --> 01:00:20.150
So I'm over it now.

01:00:21.522 --> 01:00:23.730
STEVEN PINKER: In fact so
what you are going through,

01:00:23.730 --> 01:00:25.271
and probably many
people in this room

01:00:25.271 --> 01:00:28.480
have gone through
our own lifetimes

01:00:28.480 --> 01:00:32.950
is what E.B. White never went
through in the transition

01:00:32.950 --> 01:00:38.340
from to contact as a neologism
to a part of every day English.

01:00:38.340 --> 01:00:39.780
And so this happens.

01:00:39.780 --> 01:00:42.780
Whether or not you're
convinced by my arguments

01:00:42.780 --> 01:00:45.180
that incentivize
is a useful word,

01:00:45.180 --> 01:00:46.630
it doesn't matter what we think.

01:00:46.630 --> 01:00:49.700
If people use it, it becomes
entrenched in the language.

01:00:49.700 --> 01:00:52.310
Yes, the dictionary
writers will include it,

01:00:52.310 --> 01:00:53.500
they have no choice.

01:00:53.500 --> 01:00:56.380
There are selling a product
that has to be useful.

01:00:56.380 --> 01:00:57.680
What does useful mean?

01:00:57.680 --> 01:01:00.590
You write according to the
way that your readers will

01:01:00.590 --> 01:01:02.660
expect words to be used.

01:01:03.920 --> 01:01:06.520
What we do int he American
Heritage Dictionary is

01:01:06.520 --> 01:01:08.340
that because it's
not-- generally,

01:01:08.340 --> 01:01:10.520
when you look something
up in a dictionary,

01:01:10.520 --> 01:01:14.240
you don't care about how
any old person on the street

01:01:14.240 --> 01:01:15.240
uses language.

01:01:15.240 --> 01:01:18.890
You have in mind a kind of
virtual audience of readers

01:01:18.890 --> 01:01:23.280
who care about language, who
expect the writer to take care

01:01:23.280 --> 01:01:24.820
in their choice of words.

01:01:24.820 --> 01:01:28.110
So we assembled a sample,
called the usage panel

01:01:28.110 --> 01:01:35.100
of about 200 journalists,
linguists, sports writers,

01:01:35.100 --> 01:01:38.010
poets, novelists, kind
of a sample of people

01:01:38.010 --> 01:01:40.750
who just have shown
they care about words.

01:01:40.750 --> 01:01:45.390
And we pole them, we ask them,
what do you think incentivize?

01:01:45.390 --> 01:01:48.400
And their decisions
will determine

01:01:48.400 --> 01:01:49.730
what goes into the dictionary.

01:01:49.730 --> 01:01:53.700
And in cases where it's
too close to 50-50,

01:01:53.700 --> 01:01:55.720
there will be a usage
note that just explains

01:01:55.720 --> 01:01:58.870
the history of the word,
explains the current reaction,

01:01:58.870 --> 01:02:02.842
and you-- the writer can then
make an informed decision.

01:02:02.842 --> 01:02:04.425
AUDIENCE: I went
through my dictionary

01:02:04.425 --> 01:02:07.226
and put post-it notes on all
my favorites usage notes.

01:02:07.226 --> 01:02:08.600
STEVEN PINKER: Of
very good, yes.

01:02:08.600 --> 01:02:10.470
AUDIENCE: To be
graduated from college,

01:02:10.470 --> 01:02:12.339
as opposed to
graduating from college.

01:02:12.339 --> 01:02:14.130
STEVEN PINKER: That's
an excellent example,

01:02:14.130 --> 01:02:16.120
because there, again,
the language is changing,

01:02:16.120 --> 01:02:19.660
there are purists who would
say it has to be graduated

01:02:19.660 --> 01:02:22.710
from college, but that's not
the way people talk anymore.

01:02:22.710 --> 01:02:24.451
AUDIENCE: Thanks very much.

01:02:24.451 --> 01:02:26.075
STEVEN PINKER: Thank
for your question.

01:02:26.645 --> 01:02:29.020
MALE SPEAKER: I apologize,
I'm afraid we'll have two more

