01:03:23.240 --> 01:03:28.870
and if you might consider
making a PSA demanding

01:03:28.870 --> 01:03:29.920
but this be abolished.

01:03:32.210 --> 01:03:34.940
STEVEN PINKER: Well
the uh, I can't do it.

01:03:34.940 --> 01:03:35.690
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:35.690 --> 01:03:36.719
I'll tell you why.

01:03:36.719 --> 01:03:38.010
AUDIENCE: You heard this right?

01:03:38.010 --> 01:03:38.843
STEVEN PINKER: Yeah.

01:03:38.843 --> 01:03:39.920
Oh yes absolutely.

01:03:39.920 --> 01:03:42.300
And I have a Dilbert
cartoon where

01:03:42.300 --> 01:03:45.780
the boss with the pointy hair
asks one of his employees,

01:03:45.780 --> 01:03:48.310
I would like to task
you with the deliverable

01:03:48.310 --> 01:03:50.490
and she and she
completely freaks out.

01:03:50.490 --> 01:03:52.960
My world is falling
apart, task is not a verb.

01:03:54.330 --> 01:03:56.420
A couple of observations--
one, it's not new.

01:03:56.420 --> 01:04:01.249
This has been going on, probably
for many number of centuries,

01:04:01.249 --> 01:04:03.290
probably at least since
the Middle English period

01:04:03.290 --> 01:04:05.430
or at least early
modern English.

01:04:05.430 --> 01:04:07.830
Again the reason that Strunk
and White had a problem

01:04:07.830 --> 01:04:11.620
with to contact is that contact
for them was only a noun,

01:04:11.620 --> 01:04:13.320
and it was turned into a verb.

01:04:13.320 --> 01:04:15.445
Now, do any of you have
a problem with contact?

01:04:15.445 --> 01:04:17.070
I don't have a problem
with to contact.

01:04:18.120 --> 01:04:22.360
And in fact, if you were to go
through any passage of prose,

01:04:22.360 --> 01:04:24.670
you would find
probably about a fifth

01:04:24.670 --> 01:04:27.260
of the verbs started
out life as nouns.

01:04:27.260 --> 01:04:30.030
We notice the new ones,
but it's a process that's

01:04:30.030 --> 01:04:31.810
been going on for
a long, long time.

01:04:31.810 --> 01:04:34.150
it's one of the things
that makes English English.

01:04:34.150 --> 01:04:38.180
And you often forget how many
verbs from nouns there are.

01:04:38.180 --> 01:04:42.960
To chair a meeting, to table
the motion, to pen your memoir,

01:04:42.960 --> 01:04:46.090
to hand me the cookies,
to foot the bill.

01:04:46.090 --> 01:04:51.590
There are-- it's only the new
ones that get under our skin.

01:04:51.590 --> 01:04:54.960
It's not that it's inherent
to the English language

01:04:54.960 --> 01:04:59.830
that verbing a noun
leads to a monstrosity.

01:04:59.830 --> 01:05:01.740
Then there's a--
but I agree, there's

01:05:01.740 --> 01:05:06.210
a lot of corporate
prose that is annoying,

01:05:06.210 --> 01:05:08.150
especially when
it's unnecessary.

01:05:08.150 --> 01:05:10.190
But there are ones
that will earn

01:05:10.190 --> 01:05:14.320
a foothold in the language
because as with incentivize

01:05:14.320 --> 01:05:19.450
they not only capture a meaning
while omitting needless words,

01:05:19.450 --> 01:05:22.770
but they add the extra
meaning that this is now

01:05:22.770 --> 01:05:26.190
a conventional,
direct, causal process.

01:05:26.190 --> 01:05:29.780
And that's why task
started to creep in.

01:05:29.780 --> 01:05:33.810
Who knows whether it will last,
or be a fad word like some

01:05:33.810 --> 01:05:35.740
of the ones for
the "Mad Men" era.

01:05:37.330 --> 01:05:42.290
But there's nothing we
can do, some new verbs

01:05:42.290 --> 01:05:45.506
will come from nouns
and vice versa.

01:05:45.506 --> 01:05:46.925
AUDIENCE: Trying to [INAUDIBLE].

01:05:46.925 --> 01:05:48.175
STEVEN PINKER: [LAUGHTER] Yes.

01:05:48.817 --> 01:05:50.240
Last question.

01:05:50.240 --> 01:05:53.650
Maybe say the serenity
prayer, accept the changes

01:05:53.650 --> 01:05:55.920
that you can't do
anything about.

01:05:57.074 --> 01:05:59.240
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned
literally a couple times,

01:05:59.240 --> 01:06:01.286
and how horrifying it can be.

01:06:01.286 --> 01:06:02.660
And there's also
some other words

01:06:02.660 --> 01:06:05.450
like that have evolved to use be
used the opposite of what they

01:06:05.450 --> 01:06:08.710
mean, like peruse, people use to
mean scan quickly when it means

01:06:08.710 --> 01:06:10.410
to pour over in detail.

01:06:10.410 --> 01:06:11.600
STEVEN PINKER: Yes, peruse.

01:06:11.600 --> 01:06:13.599
AUDIENCE: I'm all for the
evolution of language,

01:06:13.599 --> 01:06:15.370
but it seems like
not really productive

01:06:15.370 --> 01:06:18.580
to have words evolve to mean
the opposite of what they mean.

01:06:18.580 --> 01:06:20.630
And I was wondering what
you think about that.

01:06:20.630 --> 01:06:21.504
STEVEN PINKER: Right.

01:06:21.504 --> 01:06:24.780
Well there is this
category sometimes called

01:06:24.780 --> 01:06:26.340
a contranyms or autoantonyms.

01:06:27.750 --> 01:06:30.450
Things like to dust,
which can either

01:06:30.450 --> 01:06:33.260
mean to put dust on,
as in crop dusting,

01:06:33.260 --> 01:06:35.915
or to take dust
away as in a duster.

01:06:37.730 --> 01:06:39.135
To sanction, to table.

01:06:40.460 --> 01:06:43.490
Often what happens
is that words will--

01:06:43.490 --> 01:06:48.170
a word will start off and then
have varies near synonyms that

01:06:48.170 --> 01:06:50.010
have slightly different
meanings and then

01:06:50.010 --> 01:06:53.590
one meaning will give rise
to another until they meet

01:06:53.590 --> 01:06:57.860
and have sentences that
are the direct opposite.

01:06:57.860 --> 01:07:01.710
It doesn't happen all that
often and usually these things

01:07:01.710 --> 01:07:03.280
are clear in context.

01:07:03.280 --> 01:07:06.350
The vast majority of words
have more than one meaning.

01:07:06.350 --> 01:07:08.390
You just flip over
dictionary to any word,

01:07:08.390 --> 01:07:10.670
and it's meaning one,
meaning two, meaning three,

01:07:10.670 --> 01:07:14.530
and generally they are
distinguished by context.

01:07:14.530 --> 01:07:19.790
They can survive side by
side, so the word literate

01:07:19.790 --> 01:07:23.350
can mean either actually
capable of reading,

01:07:23.350 --> 01:07:25.590
or it could mean sophisticated.

01:07:25.590 --> 01:07:28.770
Conservative can
mean on the right

01:07:28.770 --> 01:07:30.550
of the American
political spectrum

01:07:30.550 --> 01:07:32.259
or resistant to change.

01:07:32.259 --> 01:07:33.800
And so you have
conservative liberal,

01:07:33.800 --> 01:07:35.360
and it's not an oxymoron.

01:07:35.360 --> 01:07:36.935
So word meanings can coexist.

01:07:38.380 --> 01:07:40.940
In terms of doing
something about it

01:07:40.940 --> 01:07:49.270
I quote the famous exchange
between Margaret Fuller who

01:07:49.270 --> 01:07:52.050
once wrote, I
accept the universe.

01:07:52.050 --> 01:07:55.490
And Thomas Carlyle who
said, god, you better.

01:07:55.490 --> 01:07:57.700
Language change is
going to happen,

01:07:57.700 --> 01:08:01.570
and there's almost nothing
that one can do about it.

01:08:02.760 --> 01:08:06.430
It doesn't mean that language
degenerates or deteriorates

01:08:06.430 --> 01:08:10.610
though because often the
sloppy meanings that we dislike

01:08:10.610 --> 01:08:13.860
can survive side by side
with the precise meaning

01:08:13.860 --> 01:08:15.000
that we do like.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:17.899
And it's interesting to go
back in the history of usage

01:08:17.899 --> 01:08:21.460
and find the same issues
that annoy people today

01:08:21.460 --> 01:08:23.880
were annoying people
a century ago.

01:08:23.880 --> 01:08:27.510
So if you're one of the
people-- one of those who likes

01:08:27.510 --> 01:08:30.890
the word disinterested to mean
without a vested interest as

01:08:30.890 --> 01:08:32.649
opposed to being a
synonym for bored.

01:08:34.050 --> 01:08:36.979
And you worry if people use
disinterested to mean cored,

01:08:36.979 --> 01:08:40.120
we're going to lose that lovely
word disinterested meaning

01:08:40.120 --> 01:08:42.214
unbiased or without
a best interest.

01:08:42.214 --> 01:08:43.880
But people have been
using disinterested

01:08:43.880 --> 01:08:46.890
to mean bored for
centuries, and we still

01:08:46.890 --> 01:08:51.290
have the more precise meaning
without a vested interest in.

01:08:51.290 --> 01:08:56.790
So language change does not
imply language degeneration.

01:08:56.790 --> 01:08:58.950
Often the more precise
word is available.

01:08:58.950 --> 01:09:01.930
And literally is another
example, a lot of people

01:09:01.930 --> 01:09:04.073
use it to me as a kind
of an intensifier,

01:09:04.073 --> 01:09:04.864
a bit of hyperbole.

01:09:06.080 --> 01:09:08.290
But there's still cases
in which you use literally

01:09:08.290 --> 01:09:09.980
to mean literally
it's clear in context

01:09:09.980 --> 01:09:11.479
that that's the way
you're using it.

01:09:13.058 --> 01:09:15.224
MALE SPEAKER: Thank you
very much, Professor Pinker,

01:09:15.224 --> 01:09:16.160
it's been a joy.

01:09:18.470 --> 01:09:21.450
And thank you all for coming.

